    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <opener>
                <dateline rend="right">
                    <name type="place">Camden,</name><!--<ptr target="med.00630_n5"/>-->
                    <date when="1887-02-25">Feb. 25, '87, P. M.</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>Am sitting here by the window in the little front room down stairs, well wrapt
                up&#8212;for though bright &#38; sunny it is a cold freezing day&#8212;have had my
                dinner (of rare stewed oysters, some toasted graham bread &#38; a cup of
                tea&#8212;relished all)&#8212;am about as usual&#8212;ups &#38; downs&#8212;had
                rather a bad day yesterday&#8212;lay on the lounge most of the day&#8212;now
                better&#8212;the worst is my enforced house-imprisonment, sometimes two weeks at a
                time&#8212;Spirits &#38; heart though mainly gay, which is the best half of the
                    battle<ptr target="med.00754_n1"/>&#8212;Love &#38; comfort to you, my
                friends&#8212;your wives &#38; all&#8212;Write often as you can&#8212;(monotony is
                now the word of my life)&#8212;</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>Walt Whitman</signed>
            </closer>
            <postscript> 
                <p>When read send to John Burroughs, West Park, Ulster County, New York.<ptr
                        target="med.00754_n2"/></p>
            </postscript>
        </body>
